&lt;U+04AE&gt;&lt;U+04AF&gt; and &lt;U+04E8&gt;&lt;U+04E9&gt; are sometimes also written as &lt;U+0407&gt;&lt;U+0457&gt; and &lt;U+0404&gt;&lt;U+0454&gt;.80
Historical Mongolian
 The earliest surviving Mongolian text is the Stele of Yis&lt;U+00FC&gt;ngge, a report on sports in Mongolian script on stone, that is most often dated at the verge of 1224 and 1225.81 Other early sources are written in Mongolian, Phagspa (decrees), Chinese (The Secret History of the Mongols), Arabic (dictionaries) and a few Western scripts.82 These comprise the Middle Mongolian language that was spoken from the 13th to the early 15th83 or late 16th century.84 The documents in Mongolian script show some distinct linguistic characteristics and are therefore often distinguished by terming their language &quot;Preclassical Mongolian&quot;.85 The next distinct period is Classical Mongolian that is dated from the 17th to the 19th century. It is a written language with a high degree of standardization in orthography and syntax that sets it quite apart from the subsequent Modern Mongolian. The most notable documents in this language are the Mongolian Kanjur and Tanjur86 as well as several chronicles.87 In 1686, the Soyombo script (Buddhist texts) was created, giving distinctive evidence on early classical Mongolian phonological peculiarities.88
Changes in phonology
Consonants
Middle Mongolian documents show only two velar plosives  and  (and one allophone for each), but in some instances the  disappeared and in others not. There is no hint as to how this might be related to contextual factors, and while there is a hypothesis that this is related to distinctive vowel length or stress,89 it is disputed whether there is any factual evidence for this. Now there is a word-initial  that disappeared during the Middle Mongolian stage. This might be the same phoneme as one of the instances of  (possibly ). Thus, it is likely that x &lt;U+2192&gt; h &lt;U+2192&gt; &lt;U+00D8&gt;.90 Eg Phagspa , Preclassical Mongolian , reconstructed in Proto-Mongolic as *haran &lt;U+2018&gt;person&lt;U+2019&gt;, became Modern Mongolian .91 Phagspa &lt;U+010D&gt;aqa&lt;U+2019&gt;an, Preclassical &lt;U+010D&gt;a&lt;U+03B3&gt;a&lt;U+03B3&gt;an,92 reconstructed for Late Pre-Proto-Mongolic as  &lt;U+2018&gt;white&lt;U+2019&gt;, became Modern Mongolian . As also apparent from this example, affricates were fronted in Northern Modern Mongolian dialects such as Khalkha.  was spirantized to  in Ulaanbaatar Khalkha and the Mongolian dialects south of it, eg Preclassical Mongolian &lt;k&lt;U+00FC&gt;nd&lt;U+00FC&gt;&gt;, reconstructed as  &lt;U+2018&gt;heavy&lt;U+2019&gt;, became Modern Mongolian 93 (but in the vinicity of Bayankhongor and Baruun-Urt, many speakers will say ).94 Originally word-final /n/ turned into /&lt;U+014B&gt;/; if  was originally followed by a vowel that later dropped, it remained unchanged, eg  became , but  became . After i-breaking,  became phonemic. Consonants in words containing back vowels that were followed by  in Proto-Mongolian became palatalized in Modern Mongolian. In some words, word-final  was dropped with most case forms, but still appears with the ablative, dative and genitive.95
Vowels
Proto-Mongolic had . First,  and  were pharyngealized to  and , then  and  were velarized to  and . Thus, the vowel harmony shifted from a velar to a pharyngeal paradigm.  in the first syllable of back-vocalic words was assimilated to the following vowel; in word-initial position it became .  followed by  was rounded to . VhV and VjV sequences where the second vowel was any vowel but  were monophthongized. Short vowels in any syllable but the first were deleted from the phonetic representation of the word; long vowels in these positions became short vowels.96
Eg  ( becomes ,  disappears) &lt;U+2192&gt;  (instable n drops; vowel reduction) &lt;U+2192&gt; jama(n) &lt;U+2018&gt;goat&lt;U+2019&gt;
and  (regressive rounding assimilation) &lt;U+2192&gt;  (vowel velarization) &lt;U+2192&gt;  (vowel reduction) &lt;U+2192&gt; oms- &lt;U+2018&gt;to wear&lt;U+2019&gt;
Changes in morphology
Nominal system
 While most case suffixes did change somewhat in form, ie were shortened, most of the modern case system remained intact; important changes occurred with the comitative and the dative.97 The Middle Mongolian comitative &lt;-lu&lt;U+03B3&gt;-a&gt; could not be used attributively, but it was replaced by the suffix &lt;-taj&gt; that originally derived adjectives denoting possession of the stem from nouns, eg  &lt;U+2018&gt;having a horse&lt;U+2019&gt; became &lt;mor&lt;U+2019&gt;toj&gt; &lt;U+2018&gt;having a horse/with a horse&lt;U+2019&gt;. As this adjective functioned parallel to &lt;&lt;U+00FC&gt;gej&gt; &lt;U+2018&gt;not having&lt;U+2019&gt;, it has been suggested that a &lt;U+201C&gt;privative case&lt;U+201D&gt; (&lt;U+2018&gt;without&lt;U+2019&gt;) has been introduced into Mongolian.98 There have been three different case suffixes in the dative-locative-directive domain that are grouped in different ways: &lt;-a&gt; as locative and &lt;-dur&gt;, &lt;-da&gt; as dative99 or &lt;-da&gt; and &lt;-a&gt; as dative and &lt;-dur&gt; as locative,100 in both cases with some functional overlapping. As &lt;-dur&gt; seems to be grammaticalized from  &lt;U+2018&gt;within&lt;U+2019&gt;, thus indicating a span of time,101 the second account seems to be more likely. Of these, &lt;-da&gt; got lost, &lt;-dur&gt; was first reduced to &lt;-du&gt; and then to /d/102 and &lt;-a&gt; only survived in a few frozen environments.103 Finally, the directive of modern Mongolian &lt;-ruu&gt; has been innovated from &lt;uru&lt;U+03B3&gt;u&gt; 'downwards'.104 Gender agreement was abandoned.105
Verbal system
Middle Mongolian had a slightly greater set of declarative final verb suffix forms106 and a smaller number of participles which were less likely to be used as finite predicates.107 The linking converb &lt;-n&gt; became confined to stable verb combinations,108 while the number of converbs somewhat increased.109 The gender and number distinction exhibited by some final verbs got lost.110
Changes in syntax
Neutral word order in clauses with pronominal subject changed from object&lt;U+2013&gt;predicate&lt;U+2013&gt;subject to subject&lt;U+2013&gt;object&lt;U+2013&gt;predicate, eg
K&lt;U+00F6&gt;kse&lt;U+00FC&gt; sabraq &lt;U+00FC&gt;g&lt;U+00FC&gt;.le-run 'ayyi. yeke uge ugu.le-d ta ...' kee-j&lt;U+00FC&gt;&lt;U+00FC&gt;.y.
K. s. speak-converb alas big word speak-Past you say-nonfuture
'K&lt;U+00F6&gt;kse&lt;U+00FC&gt; sabraq spoke saying &quot;Alas. You speak a great boast. ...&quot;'111
The negation of verbs shifted from negation particles preceding final verbs to a negation particle following participles; thus, as final verbs could no longer be negated, their paradigm of negation was filled by particles.112 For example, Preclassical Mongolian  'did not come' vs. modern spoken Mongolian &lt;ireeg&lt;U+00FC&gt;j&gt; (modern written Mongolian &lt;irege &lt;U+00FC&gt;gei&gt;) 'did not come (yet)' or &lt;irseng&lt;U+00FC&gt;j&gt; 'did not come (then)'.
